# Meta Note - Step 003 Exploration 001

## What Worked

- Reducing every connected two-triad shared-mode picture to the canonical form
  `{ (a,b,a+b), (a,c,a+c) }`
  exposed which drawings were genuinely new second-budget seeds and which only
  recycled the failed first-budget pseudo-support.
- Separating the generic five-orbit fan from the four-orbit
  mirror/parallelogram subfamily prevented cosmetic re-centered drawings from
  being counted as distinct seeds.

## Reusable Lesson

- In support-search steps above the first rung, classify by exact support
  identity after conjugation and triad relabeling before doing closure.
  Otherwise the step will confuse re-centered copies and first-budget
  decorations with new ladder-level seeds.

## Caution

- A two-triad picture that fits inside the old mirror-complete one-triad
  support is not a genuine second-rung seed even if it displays two distinct
  triad equations.

---
# Meta Note - Step 003 Exploration 002

## What Worked

- Splitting the closure audit by canonical family made the obstruction sharper:
  the generic fan spills through cross-triad forcing, while the
  mirror/parallelogram cluster spills through the first
  `a ± 2b`
  targets.
- A small direct helical-coefficient probe across all seed sign assignments was
  enough to confirm that the first new targets stay live instead of disappearing
  under sign-sector choices.

## Reusable Lesson

- When a support budget is killed by the first new wavevector orbit, a compact
  representative coefficient audit is often enough.
  The step does not need full projected ODEs before writing a current-budget
  spill verdict.

## Caution

- Representative coefficient checks can justify the first spill target, but
  they do not by themselves prove a full infinite-closure theorem.
  Keep the claim budget-limited.

---
# Meta Note - Step 003 Exploration 003

## What Worked

- Treating the tidy second-budget pictures as pseudo-survivors only for the
  purpose of an admissible-enlargement test kept the step honest while still
  explaining why Chain Step 3 is unearned.
- Re-adding the first forced orbit before rerunning closure showed that both
  pseudo-survivors fail for the same reason as the raw closure audit:
  pruning the first spill mode was doing all the apparent stabilizing work.

## Reusable Lesson

- When no honest survivor remains, the enlargement pass should stress-test the
  most tempting over-pruned picture rather than pretend a true survivor exists.

## Caution

- A clean second-budget negative still does not authorize mission-level
  termination or self-escalation to the next rung.

